---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import AdUnit from '../../components/AdUnit.astro';

const faq = [
  {
    question: "What causes latency between cloud regions?",
    answer: "Latency between cloud regions is dominated by three factors: geographic distance (which sets a hard physical lower bound based on the speed of light in fiber), the number of network hops between backbone peering points, and congestion or queuing in intermediate routers. Cloud providers like AWS, GCP, and Azure maintain private backbone networks between their own regions, which typically have lower latency than public internet paths. However, inter-provider traffic (e.g., a user on AWS eu-west-1 hitting an Azure service in West Europe) must traverse public internet exchange points (IXPs), adding 5–30ms of extra overhead. Geographic distance alone explains roughly 80% of observed RTT variance across regions."
  },
  {
    question: "How does a multi-region active-active architecture differ from active-passive?",
    answer: "In active-active, all regions simultaneously serve live traffic and accept writes. Requests are routed to the nearest region, achieving the lowest possible latency for users worldwide. The complexity cost is real-time data replication and conflict resolution — you need eventual consistency guarantees (CRDTs, vector clocks) or a globally distributed database like CockroachDB, PlanetScale, or AWS Aurora Global. In active-passive, one region ('active') handles all writes and the others ('passive') serve read traffic from replicas. Failover is simpler but write latency for non-primary users is high (users in Asia hitting a primary in US East add 150–200ms of write latency). Active-passive is the right choice for most teams until they hit meaningful global write volume."
  },
  {
    question: "When should I use a CDN instead of multi-region deployments?",
    answer: "A CDN solves latency for static and cacheable content (HTML, JS, CSS, images, API responses with TTL). It is cheaper, simpler to deploy, and delivers sub-10ms TTFB to users worldwide by serving from 200+ edge PoPs. Multi-region deployments solve latency for dynamic, personalized, or write-heavy workloads that cannot be cached. The practical rule: if your response is the same for all users or can be cached for 1+ second, use a CDN. If your response requires a database read of user-specific data, prefer regional deployment close to your users. Most production architectures combine both: CDN for static assets and cached API responses, regional origins for dynamic data. Cloudflare Workers and Fastly Compute@Edge blur this line by running full compute logic at the CDN edge."
  },
  {
    question: "What is anycast routing and how does it reduce latency?",
    answer: "Anycast is a routing technique where multiple servers share the same IP address. BGP routing automatically directs each user's packets to the topologically nearest node advertising that address. Cloudflare, AWS Route 53, and Google Cloud DNS all use anycast for their global networks. When you resolve a Cloudflare-proxied hostname, all users in Tokyo, London, and São Paulo get the same IP but are routed to the nearest Cloudflare PoP — without any DNS-level geo-routing. Anycast is ideal for UDP services (DNS, NTP) and stateless HTTP/HTTPS because TCP connections land on the nearest server naturally. For stateful workloads, DNS-based geo-routing (Route 53 Latency Routing, GCP Traffic Director) is more appropriate since you need session stickiness."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the theoretical minimum latency between two locations?",
    answer: "The absolute minimum round-trip time between two points is determined by the speed of light in fiber optic cable (~200,000 km/s, or about 2/3 of the speed of light in vacuum). The formula is: RTT_min = (distance_km / 200,000) × 2 × 1000 ms. For example, New York to London (~5,500 km) has a theoretical minimum RTT of 55ms. Real-world RTT is typically 1.3–2× the theoretical minimum due to: non-straight fiber cable routes, signal amplification delays, processing overhead in routers and switches, and TCP/TLS handshake overhead. If you are seeing latency more than 2.5× the theoretical minimum, it suggests suboptimal routing or peering — worth investigating with traceroute or tools like PerfOps."
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Multi-Cloud Region Latency Calculator — AWS, GCP, Azure RTT Estimator"
  description="Estimate round-trip latency from your location to every AWS, GCP, and Azure region. Color-coded results, best-region recommendations, active-active vs active-passive strategy guide, and speed-of-light theoretical minimum calculator."
  tool="Cloud Region Latency Calculator, AWS Region Latency, GCP Latency, Azure Region RTT, Multi-Cloud Latency Estimator, Cloud Region Picker"
  faq={faq}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebApplication",
    "name": "Multi-Cloud Region Latency Calculator",
    "url": "https://devplaybook.cc/tools/cloud-region-latency-calculator",
    "description": "Estimate latency from your source location to AWS, GCP, and Azure regions worldwide. Hardcoded RTT lookup table, color-coded results, and deployment recommendations.",
    "applicationCategory": "DeveloperApplication",
    "operatingSystem": "Any",
    "offers": { "@type": "Offer", "price": "0", "priceCurrency": "USD" }
  })} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Multi-Cloud Region Latency Calculator</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
    Select your source location and cloud provider(s) to estimate round-trip latency to every region.
    Results are color-coded: <span class="text-green-400 font-medium">green &lt;50ms</span>,
    <span class="text-yellow-400 font-medium">yellow 50–150ms</span>,
    <span class="text-red-400 font-medium">red &gt;150ms</span>.
    Based on realistic approximate RTT values from public benchmarks. Runs entirely in your browser.
  </p>
  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> AWS, GCP &amp; Azure regions</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Best-region recommendations</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Speed-of-light theoretical minimum</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Multi-region deployment strategy</span>
  </div>

  <!-- Controls -->
  <div class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-5 mb-5">
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-5">
      <!-- Source Region -->
      <div>
        <label class="block text-sm font-medium mb-2" for="source-select">Your Location (Source Region)</label>
        <select id="source-select"
          class="w-full bg-bg-surface border border-border rounded-lg px-3 py-2.5 text-sm focus:outline-none focus:border-primary">
          <!-- Filled by JS -->
        </select>
      </div>
      <!-- Provider checkboxes -->
      <div>
        <label class="block text-sm font-medium mb-2">Cloud Provider(s)</label>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3" id="provider-toggles">
          <label class="flex items-center gap-2 cursor-pointer select-none">
            <input type="checkbox" id="toggle-aws" checked
              class="w-4 h-4 accent-orange-400 cursor-pointer" />
            <span class="text-sm font-medium text-orange-400">AWS</span>
          </label>
          <label class="flex items-center gap-2 cursor-pointer select-none">
            <input type="checkbox" id="toggle-gcp" checked
              class="w-4 h-4 accent-blue-400 cursor-pointer" />
            <span class="text-sm font-medium text-blue-400">GCP</span>
          </label>
          <label class="flex items-center gap-2 cursor-pointer select-none">
            <input type="checkbox" id="toggle-azure" checked
              class="w-4 h-4 accent-cyan-400 cursor-pointer" />
            <span class="text-sm font-medium text-cyan-400">Azure</span>
          </label>
        </div>
        <p class="text-xs text-text-muted mt-2">Select one or more providers to compare</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Recommendations -->
  <div id="recommendations-panel" class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-5 mb-5 hidden">
    <h2 class="text-base font-semibold mb-3">Deployment Recommendations</h2>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
      <div id="reco-under50" class="bg-bg-surface border border-green-500/30 rounded-lg p-3">
        <div class="text-xs font-semibold text-green-400 mb-2">Best Regions (&lt;50ms)</div>
        <div id="reco-under50-list" class="space-y-1 text-sm"></div>
      </div>
      <div id="reco-under150" class="bg-bg-surface border border-yellow-500/30 rounded-lg p-3">
        <div class="text-xs font-semibold text-yellow-400 mb-2">Acceptable Regions (50–150ms)</div>
        <div id="reco-under150-list" class="space-y-1 text-sm"></div>
      </div>
      <div id="reco-primary" class="bg-bg-surface border border-primary/30 rounded-lg p-3">
        <div class="text-xs font-semibold text-primary mb-2">Recommended Primary</div>
        <div id="reco-primary-text" class="text-sm"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Results table -->
  <div class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-5 mb-5">
    <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-4 flex-wrap gap-3">
      <h2 class="text-base font-semibold">Latency Results</h2>
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-xs">
        <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="w-3 h-3 rounded-sm bg-green-500/30 border border-green-500 inline-block"></span> &lt;50ms — Excellent</span>
        <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="w-3 h-3 rounded-sm bg-yellow-500/20 border border-yellow-500 inline-block"></span> 50–150ms — Acceptable</span>
        <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="w-3 h-3 rounded-sm bg-red-500/20 border border-red-500 inline-block"></span> &gt;150ms — High</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div id="results-container" class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-3">
      <!-- Filled by JS -->
    </div>
    <p id="no-provider-msg" class="hidden text-text-muted text-sm text-center py-4">
      Select at least one cloud provider above.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Speed of light calculator -->
  <div class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-5 mb-5">
    <h2 class="text-base font-semibold mb-1">Speed-of-Light Theoretical Minimum RTT</h2>
    <p class="text-xs text-text-muted mb-4">
      Calculate the absolute minimum round-trip latency based on fiber optic propagation speed (~200,000 km/s).
      Real-world RTT is typically 1.3–2× this value due to routing overhead.
    </p>
    <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4 items-start sm:items-end">
      <div class="flex-1">
        <label class="block text-sm font-medium mb-1.5" for="distance-input">Distance (km)</label>
        <input id="distance-input" type="number" value="5500" min="0" max="20000" step="100"
